<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-867-652  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 867 652.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Oct 30 1989 v15 n21 p19(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>White House pushes for advances in supercomputing; the Bushadministration wants to allocate nearly $2 billion over five yearsfor a high-speed computing network.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Greene, Tony.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The George Bush administration will push for a $2 billionexpenditure to improve communication links between supercomputersand create a nationwide high-speed computing network.andP;  Thehigh-performance computing (HPC) initiative would link more than1,000 supercomputers at research sites beginning in 1991.andO;Proponents believe the HPC initiative is the precursor to anationwide fiber-optic network that would supply households andoffices with access to high-definition television, electroniclibraries and databases.andP;  The initiative would improve the US'sinternational HPC profile, speed the pace of HPC innovation bymoving them more rapidly into the scientific mainstream, andsupport economic competitiveness by using HPC for analysis, designand manufacturing.andP;  The federal government, private sector anduniversity community would all collaborate to implement thenetwork.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Future of ComputingNetwork ModelsSupercomputersGovernment Funding.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   High-Performance Computing initiative funding proposal comparison.andO;(graph)Person:    Bush, George (telecommunication policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>